    <annotation>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>An Italian Gentleman, limned A palme tre, with this Posy:</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Flectimur obsequio, non viribus.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>"We bend out of compliance, not because of force" [Stone, 2013].</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Heliotropium, [the] Marigold,</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Vertitur ad solem.</marginalia_text>
                    <X-ref person="Ovid" book_title="Metamorphoses" text="Vertitur ad solem." language="LA"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Heliotropium, [the] Marigold, "it turns towards the sun".</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Remora, A little fish, stayeth, and howldeth fast, A great ship. Hippolito Girami,
                    a millanese, bare A Sword, With A Serpent Winding abowt it, &amp; A laurel Garland in [the] Serpents mowth: With this mot,
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Hippolito Giramo"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>His ducibus.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Remora, A little fish, stayeth, and howldeth fast, A great ship. Hippolito Girami,
                a millanese, bare A Sword, With A Serpent Winding abowt it, &amp; A laurel Garland in [the] Serpents mowth: With this mot, for these leaders.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Bulrushes, in [the] middest of A riuer, bow, but breake not, ether with waue, or Winde: [their] posy,</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Flectimur, non frangimur vndis. Quale illud: Generosus animus ducitur, non trahitur.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>"We are bend, but not broken by waves" [Stone, 2013].  What kind is that: a noble character is led, not dragged.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>[the] Foxes mot:</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Simul astu, et dentibus vtor.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>At the same time I make use of cunning and teeth.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
